<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<assessmentItem xmlns="http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqti_v2p1"
                xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
                xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqti_v2p1 http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqti_v2p1.xsd"
                identifier="IntroductionToEquations" title="Introduction to Equations" adaptive="false"
                timeDependent="false">
    <responseDeclaration identifier="RESPONSE" cardinality="multiple" baseType="identifier"/>
    <outcomeDeclaration identifier="SCORE" cardinality="single" baseType="float"/>
    <itemBody>
        <p>
            Lets us recall the match stick pattern of forming triangle. For our convenience, figure is redrawn below
        </p>
        <p>
            <p>1)</p>
            <img src="images/matchstick-triangle-1.png" height="100px" width="120px" alt="Match Stick Triangle 1"/>
        </p>
        <p>
            <p>2)</p>
            <img src="images/matchstick-triangle-2.png" height="100px" width="240px" alt="Match Stick Triangle 2"/>
        </p>
        <p>
            <p>3)</p>
            <img src="images/matchstick-triangle-3.png" height="100px" width="360px" alt="Match Stick Triangle 3"/>
        </p>
        <p>
            Table below shows the number of match sticks required for different number of triangles formed.
        </p>
        <table class="table table-bordered">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Number of triangles</th>
                    <th>1</th>
                    <th>2</th>
                    <th>3</th>
                    <th>4</th>
                    <th>5</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>Number of match sticks used</td>
                    <td>
                        3
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        6
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        9
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        12
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        15
                    </td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
            We know that the number of match sticks required is given by the rule
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            ,
            where
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            is number of triangles formed.
            <br/>
            Lets think differently, "We know how to find the number of match sticks required for given number of
            triangles.
            What about the other way round? How does one find the number of triangles formed, given the number of match
            sticks" ?
        </p>
        <p>
            Lets ask ourselves a definite question. How many triangles are formed if the number of match sticks give is
            12?
            This means we have to find the number of triangles, given the number of match sticks is 12. So,
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            = 12
        </p>
        <p>
            Here, we have a condition to be satisfied by the variable
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            . This condition is an example of an<code>equation</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Our question can be answered by looking at below table. Look at the various values of
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            . if
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            = 1, the number of match sticks is 3. Clearly, the condition is not satisfied, because 3 is no 12.
            We go on checking
            <table class="table table-bordered">
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>
                            <m:math>
                                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                </m:mstyle>
                            </m:math>
                        </th>
                        <th>
                            <m:math>
                                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                                    <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                </m:mstyle>
                            </m:math>
                        </th>
                        <th>Condition satisfied.? Yes/No</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            1
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            3
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            No
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            2
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            6
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            No
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            3
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            9
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            No
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            4
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            12
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            Yes
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            5
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            15
                        </td>
                        <td>
                            No
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </p>
        <p>
            We find that only if
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            = 4, the condition i.e the equation
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            = 12
            is satisfied. For any value of
            <m:math>
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            other than 4, the equation is not satisfied.
        </p>
        <p>
            To summarise,
            <strong>
                Any equation like the above, is a condition on a variable. It is satisfied only for a definite value of
                the variable.
            </strong>
        </p>
    </itemBody>
</assessmentItem>
